<script>
const visited = new Set();
let currentTopic = 0;
let currentSection = 0;

const topics = [

{
  title: "Algorithms & Flowcharts",
  color: "purple",
  sections: ["Notes", "Mind Map", "Flowchart", "ELI10", "Problem Solving", "Practice MCQs", "Short Qs", "Exam Strategy"],
  content: [
    // 0: Notes
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Complete Notes — Algorithms & Flowcharts</h2>
      <p><span class="badge badge-purple">Definition</span> An <strong>algorithm</strong> is a finite, ordered set of well-defined instructions to solve a problem or accomplish a task. It must have: Input, Output, Definiteness, Finiteness, and Effectiveness.</p>
      <h3>Properties of a Good Algorithm</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Input:</strong> Zero or more inputs accepted</li>
        <li><strong>Output:</strong> At least one output produced</li>
        <li><strong>Definiteness:</strong> Each step is clear and unambiguous</li>
        <li><strong>Finiteness:</strong> Algorithm terminates after finite steps</li>
        <li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> Each step must be feasible</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Flowchart Symbols</h3>
      <table class="tt">
        <tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Shape</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Terminal</td><td>Oval / Rounded rect</td><td>Start / End of program</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Process</td><td>Rectangle</td><td>Calculation or operation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Decision</td><td>Diamond</td><td>Yes/No condition (if/else)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Input/Output</td><td>Parallelogram</td><td>Read input / Display output</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Flow Arrow</td><td>Arrow</td><td>Direction of flow</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Connector</td><td>Circle</td><td>Connect parts of large flowchart</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Types of Control Structures</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sequence:</strong> Steps executed one after another in order</li>
        <li><strong>Selection:</strong> Decision-based branching (IF-THEN-ELSE)</li>
        <li><strong>Iteration/Loop:</strong> Repeating steps (WHILE, FOR, DO-WHILE)</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="warn-box"><p><strong>Common Mistakes:</strong> Forgetting Start/End terminals · Missing arrows · Using wrong shapes · Infinite loops (no exit condition) · Off-by-one errors in loops</p></div>
      <h3>Algorithm Characteristics vs Flowcharts</h3>
      <p>Algorithm = written in pseudocode/English steps. Flowchart = visual/graphical representation of the same algorithm. Both are used in the <strong>design phase</strong> of programming.</p>
      <h3>Real-Life Example</h3>
      <p>Making tea: Start → Boil water → Add tea bag → Wait 3 min → Add milk/sugar → End. This is an algorithm. Drawing it with symbols = flowchart.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Important Exam Focus Areas</h2>
      <span class="badge badge-red">Must Know</span><span class="badge badge-amber">Frequently Tested</span>
      <ul style="margin-top:0.5rem">
        <li>Identify the correct flowchart symbol for a given operation</li>
        <li>Draw a flowchart for: finding max of 3 numbers, grade calculator, even/odd check</li>
        <li>Convert pseudocode to flowchart</li>
        <li>Trace through a given flowchart and find the output</li>
        <li>Difference between algorithm and program</li>
        <li>Identify which control structure is used in a flowchart</li>
      </ul>
    </div>`,

    // 1: Mind Map
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Mind Map — Algorithms & Flowcharts</h2>
      <div class="mindmap">
<span class="root">ALGORITHMS & FLOWCHARTS</span>
├── ALGORITHM
│   ├── Definition: Step-by-step instructions
│   ├── Properties
│   │   ├── Input (0 or more)
│   │   ├── Output (≥1)
│   │   ├── Definiteness (clear steps)
│   │   ├── Finiteness (must end)
│   │   └── Effectiveness (feasible)
│   └── Representation
│       ├── Pseudocode (English-like)
│       └── Flowchart (visual)
│
├── FLOWCHART SYMBOLS
│   ├── Oval → Start/End
│   ├── Rectangle → Process
│   ├── Diamond → Decision (Yes/No)
│   ├── Parallelogram → Input/Output
│   ├── Arrow → Flow direction
│   └── Circle → Connector
│
├── CONTROL STRUCTURES
│   ├── Sequence → Step 1 → Step 2 → Step 3
│   ├── Selection → IF condition THEN A ELSE B
│   └── Iteration → WHILE condition DO steps
│
└── APPLICATIONS
    ├── Sorting (bubble, selection)
    ├── Searching (linear, binary)
    └── Everyday problem solving</div>
    </div>`,

    // 2: Flowchart diagram
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Sample Flowcharts (Text Diagrams)</h2>
      <h3>Example 1: Check if a number is Even or Odd</h3>
      <div class="mono">        [START]
           |
     [Read Number N]
           |
     &lt;N % 2 == 0?&gt;
      /         \
    YES          NO
     |            |
 [Print "Even"]  [Print "Odd"]
     |            |
      \          /
         [END]</div>
      <h3>Example 2: Find Largest of 3 Numbers</h3>
      <div class="mono">        [START]
           |
    [Read A, B, C]
           |
     &lt;A &gt; B?&gt;
    /         \
  YES          NO
   |            |
&lt;A &gt; C?&gt;    &lt;B &gt; C?&gt;
  /   \       /   \
YES   NO    YES   NO
 |     |     |     |
[A]   [C]   [B]   [C]  ← largest
   \   |   /   /
    [Print Max]
         |
       [END]</div>
      <h3>Example 3: Loop — Print 1 to 5</h3>
      <div class="mono">        [START]
           |
       [i = 1]
           |
      &lt;i &lt;= 5?&gt;
      /         \
    YES          NO → [END]
     |
  [Print i]
     |
  [i = i + 1]
     |
  (loop back)</div>
      <div class="tip-box"><p><strong>Exam Tip:</strong> In a decision diamond, always label BOTH exits (YES/NO or TRUE/FALSE). Missing labels = marks deducted.</p></div>
    </div>`,

    // 3: ELI10
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Explain Like I'm 10</h2>
      <h3>What is an Algorithm?</h3>
      <p>Imagine you want to make a sandwich. You don't just randomly grab things — you follow steps: Get bread, get cheese, put cheese between bread, done! That list of steps is an <strong>algorithm</strong>. A computer follows the same idea — a list of steps to solve a problem.</p>
      <h3>What is a Flowchart?</h3>
      <p>A flowchart is like a <strong>map of the algorithm</strong>. Instead of writing steps in words, you draw them using special shapes and arrows. It's like a treasure map — you follow the arrows and shapes until you reach the "End" treasure!</p>
      <h3>Why the Diamond Shape for Decisions?</h3>
      <p>A diamond has two pointy sides — just like a decision has TWO choices: YES or NO. When you see a diamond, the computer is asking a question and will go one of two ways depending on the answer.</p>
      <h3>What's a Loop?</h3>
      <p>Imagine your mom says "eat one spoon of food" 5 times. She repeats the same instruction until you finish. That repetition is a <strong>loop</strong>. In a flowchart, the arrow goes back to repeat the steps.</p>
      <div class="tip-box"><p><strong>Memory trick:</strong> O-val = stOp/stArt. Diamond = Decision. Rect-angle = actiOn. Parallelogram = in/out-put.</p></div>
    </div>`,

    // 4: Problem Solving
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Step-by-Step Problem Solving</h2>
      <h3>How to Draw a Flowchart — 5-Step Method</h3>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-content"><strong>Identify Inputs:</strong> What data does the problem need? (e.g., "two numbers")</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-content"><strong>Identify Outputs:</strong> What should the result be? (e.g., "their sum")</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-content"><strong>Identify Decisions:</strong> Are there any YES/NO conditions? (e.g., "is it negative?")</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-content"><strong>Identify Loops:</strong> Is anything repeated? (e.g., "repeat 5 times")</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-content"><strong>Draw:</strong> Start → Inputs → Process/Decisions/Loops → Output → End</div></div>
      <h3>Worked Example: Grade Calculator</h3>
      <p>Problem: Read a score. If ≥ 60, print "Pass", otherwise "Fail".</p>
      <div class="mono">Step 1: Input = score (number)
Step 2: Output = "Pass" or "Fail"
Step 3: Decision = Is score ≥ 60?
Step 4: No loop needed

[START] → [Read score] → &lt;score ≥ 60?&gt;
  YES → [Print "Pass"] → [END]
  NO  → [Print "Fail"] → [END]</div>
      <h3>Worked Example: Sum of N numbers</h3>
      <div class="mono">Step 1: Input = N (how many), each number
Step 2: Output = total sum
Step 3: Loop = repeat N times

[START] → [Sum=0, i=1] → [Read N]
→ &lt;i ≤ N?&gt;
   YES → [Read num] → [Sum = Sum + num] → [i = i+1] → (back)
   NO  → [Print Sum] → [END]</div>
    </div>`,

    // 5: MCQs
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Practice MCQs (with answers)</h2>
      ${[
        {q:"1. Which flowchart symbol represents a decision?", opts:["a) Rectangle","b) Oval","c) Diamond","d) Parallelogram"], ans:"c) Diamond — It has two exits: YES and NO (or TRUE/FALSE)."},
        {q:"2. What does a parallelogram represent?", opts:["a) Process","b) Decision","c) Input/Output","d) Start/End"], ans:"c) Input/Output — e.g., Read a number OR Print result."},
        {q:"3. Which property ensures an algorithm terminates?", opts:["a) Definiteness","b) Finiteness","c) Effectiveness","d) Input"], ans:"b) Finiteness — An algorithm must end after a finite number of steps."},
        {q:"4. A loop in a flowchart is represented by?", opts:["a) A diamond with one exit","b) An arrow going backward","c) A rectangle alone","d) Two ovals"], ans:"b) An arrow going backward — The flow returns to an earlier step to repeat."},
        {q:"5. Which control structure uses IF-THEN-ELSE?", opts:["a) Sequence","b) Iteration","c) Selection","d) Recursion"], ans:"c) Selection — Branches based on a condition being true or false."},
        {q:"6. An algorithm differs from a program because:", opts:["a) Programs have symbols","b) Algorithms are language-independent","c) Programs have no logic","d) Algorithms need hardware"], ans:"b) Language-independent — Algorithms can be implemented in any language."},
        {q:"7. Which is NOT a property of a good algorithm?", opts:["a) Output","b) Ambiguity","c) Finiteness","d) Effectiveness"], ans:"b) Ambiguity — A good algorithm must be DEFINITE (unambiguous), not ambiguous."},
        {q:"8. The oval symbol in a flowchart represents:", opts:["a) Decision","b) Process","c) Terminal (Start/End)","d) Connector"], ans:"c) Terminal — Ovals mark the beginning and end of a flowchart."},
        {q:"9. What is pseudocode?", opts:["a) A programming language","b) English-like description of steps","c) A type of flowchart","d) Machine code"], ans:"b) English-like steps — Pseudocode describes logic informally, not in a specific language."},
        {q:"10. A flowchart with no decision diamond contains which structure only?", opts:["a) Iteration","b) Selection","c) Sequence","d) Recursion"], ans:"c) Sequence — Steps execute one after another with no branching."}
      ].map(q => `<div class="mcq-item"><p class="q">${q.q}</p>${q.opts.map(o=>`<div class="mcq-opt">${o}</div>`).join('')}<button class="show-ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns(this)">Show Answer</button><div class="mcq-ans">${q.ans}</div></div>`).join('')}
    </div>`,

    // 6: Short Qs
    `<div class="card">
      <h2>Short Questions & Answers</h2>
      ${[
        {q:"Q1. Define an algorithm and list its 5 properties.", a:"An algorithm is a finite, ordered set of unambiguous instructions to solve a problem. Properties: Input, Output, Definiteness, Finiteness, Effectiveness."},
        {q:"Q2. What is the difference between a flowchart and pseudocode?", a:"Flowchart = graphical/visual representation using symbols and arrows. Pseudocode = written description using English-like statements. Both represent the same algorithm."},
        {q:"Q3. Name the 3 control structures used in algorithms.", a:"1. Sequence (steps in order), 2. Selection (IF-THEN-ELSE branching), 3. Iteration/Loop (repeating steps while a condition holds)."},
        {q:"Q4. What symbol do you use for Input/Output in a flowchart?", a:"Parallelogram. Used for both reading input (e.g., Read X) and displaying output (e.g., Print Result)."},
        {q:"Q5. A student wrote a flowchart that never reaches END. What property is violated?", a:"Finiteness — A valid algorithm must terminate. The student's loop has no exit condition, creating an infinite loop."}
      ].map(sq=>`<div class="mcq-item"><p class="q">${sq.q}</p><button class="show-ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns(this)">Show Answer</button><div class="mcq-ans">${sq.a}</div></div>`).join('')}
      <h3>Scenario-Based (Long Questions)</h3>
      <div class="scenario-box"><div class="label">Scenario</div><p>A school wants to automate grade reporting. Students enter marks for 5 subjects. The system calculates average, then prints "Distinction" (≥85), "Pass" (≥50), or "Fail". Design the algorithm and draw a flowchart.</p><button class="show-ans-btn" onclick="toggleScenario(this)">Show Full Answer</button><div class="scenario-ans"><p><strong>Algorithm:</strong><br>1. Start<br>2. Set sum=0, i=1<br>3. While i≤5: Read mark, Sum=Sum+mark, i=i+1<br>4. Avg = Sum/5<br>5. If Avg≥85: Print "Distinction" / Elif Avg≥50: Print "Pass" / Else: Print "Fail"<br>6. End<br><br><strong>Key flowchart elements:</strong> One loop (repeat 5 times) + Two decision diamonds (≥85? and ≥50?) + Three output paths</p></div></div>
    </div>`,

    // 7: Exam Strategy
    `<div class="card">
