      <h2>Complete Notes — Network Topologies</h2>
      <p>A <strong>network topology</strong> describes the arrangement/layout of computers and devices in a network — both physically (how cables run) and logically (how data flows).</p>
      <h3>1. Bus Topology</h3>
      <p>All devices connect to a single central cable (the "bus" or backbone). Data travels in both directions along the bus.</p>
      <ul><li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Simple, cheap, easy to install</li><li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> If the bus fails, entire network goes down. Collisions occur with heavy traffic.</li><li><strong>Use:</strong> Small LANs, old Ethernet (10Base2)</li></ul>
      <h3>2. Star Topology</h3>
      <p>All devices connect to a central hub or switch. Data passes through the hub.</p>
      <ul><li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Easy to add/remove devices, failure of one node doesn't affect others, easy to troubleshoot</li><li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> Hub/switch is single point of failure. More cable needed.</li><li><strong>Use:</strong> Most common in homes and offices today (Wi-Fi router = hub)</li></ul>
      <h3>3. Ring Topology</h3>
      <p>Devices connect in a circular loop. Data travels in one (or both) direction(s) around the ring using a "token".</p>
      <ul><li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Equal access for all devices, no collisions (token-based)</li><li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> If one device fails, the whole ring can fail. Slow for large networks.</li><li><strong>Use:</strong> Token Ring networks (IBM legacy), SONET in WANs</li></ul>
      <h3>4. Mesh Topology</h3>
      <p>Every device connects directly to every other device. Full mesh = n(n-1)/2 connections.</p>
      <ul><li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Highly reliable, multiple paths for data, excellent fault tolerance</li><li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> Very expensive, complex cabling, hard to install</li><li><strong>Use:</strong> Military networks, internet backbone, banking systems</li></ul>
      <h3>5. Hybrid Topology</h3>
      <p>Combination of two or more topologies. E.g., Star-Bus or Star-Ring.</p>
      <ul><li><strong>Use:</strong> Large enterprise networks, universities, hospitals</li></ul>
      <div class="warn-box"><p><strong>Common Mistakes:</strong> Confusing physical vs logical topology · Saying hub failure = ring failure (it's star!) · Forgetting mesh formula n(n-1)/2</p></div>
