      <h2>Complete Notes — Logic Gates</h2>
      <p>Logic gates are the fundamental building blocks of digital circuits. They perform logical operations on binary inputs (0 or 1) and produce a binary output. Based on Boolean algebra.</p>
      <h3>The 7 Basic Logic Gates</h3>
      <table class="tt">
        <tr><th>Gate</th><th>Symbol</th><th>Operation</th><th>Rule (simple)</th></tr>
        <tr><td>AND</td><td>D-shape with flat left</td><td>A · B</td><td>Output 1 only if ALL inputs are 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>OR</td><td>Curved D-shape</td><td>A + B</td><td>Output 1 if ANY input is 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NOT</td><td>Triangle with circle</td><td>Ā (A-bar)</td><td>Inverts the input (flip 0↔1)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NAND</td><td>AND + circle at output</td><td>-(A·B)</td><td>Opposite of AND (universal gate)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>NOR</td><td>OR + circle at output</td><td>-(A+B)</td><td>Opposite of OR (universal gate)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XOR</td><td>OR with extra curve</td><td>A⊕B</td><td>Output 1 if inputs are DIFFERENT</td></tr>
        <tr><td>XNOR</td><td>XOR + circle</td><td>-(A⊕B)</td><td>Output 1 if inputs are SAME</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Universal Gates</h3>
      <p>NAND and NOR are called <strong>universal gates</strong> because any other gate can be built using only NAND gates (or only NOR gates). This is important for manufacturing — simpler, cheaper chips.</p>
      <div class="warn-box"><p><strong>Common Mistakes:</strong> Confusing XOR and OR (XOR is 0 when both inputs = 1!) · Forgetting NAND = NOT AND (invert AND output) · Drawing wrong symbols in diagrams</p></div>
